(10, 'Franco Corelli vocal technique[Lowered Larynx vocal technique]', 'Franco_Corelli_vocal_technique.jpg', 'franco-corelli-vocal-techniquelowered-larynx-vocal-technique', '<p style=\"text-align: center; \"><img src=\"/media/django-summernote/2023-06-15/cb6e6776-db28-4974-a4a7-fd1ef6fbfab0.png\" style=\"width: 483px; height: 264.119px;\"></p><h1 style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; color: rgb(14, 45, 73); line-height: 42px; font-size: 30px; background-color: rgb(246, 249, 251);\">Franco Corelli vocal technique[Lowered Larynx vocal technique]</h1><blockquote style=\"box-sizing: inherit; position: relative; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; padding-top: 0px; padding-right: 0px; padding-bottom: 0px; font-size: 16px; line-height: 28px; color: rgb(14, 45, 73); background-color: rgb(246, 249, 251);\">This post is about the vocal technique in the classical operatic singing since ninth century that Arturo Melocchi who is an Italian legendary operatic baritone and also a voice teacher, and Franco Corelli, who has been also an another legendary operatic dramatico and Spinto tenor which shows the most ideal vocal mechanisms to opera singing. Although many opera singers attempted to follow him, but there are lots of controversy about the efficiency of the technique because it\'s hard to catch up and difficult to lead them in to the successful career based upon the specific vocal technique.</blockquote><p style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 20px; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; color: rgb(98, 111, 131); font-family: &quot;Open Sans&quot;, sans-serif; background-color: rgb(246, 249, 251);\">Here\'s what I am saying I would like to introduce a rare mechanism of vocal technique that has been used by some acclaimed opera singers in the past centuries.&nbsp;</p><p style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 20px; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; color: rgb(98, 111, 131); font-family: &quot;Open Sans&quot;, sans-serif; background-color: rgb(246, 249, 251);\">Some treatises say that \"Lowered Larynx vocal technique\" is not the technique of Franco Corelli and Melocchi, but what I would like to say is not the simple basic mechanism of the Lowered larynx vocal technique in operatic singing. Here is the basic vocal mechanism of the \"Lowered larynx vocal technique\" that usual scholars mention about it.</p><h2 style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-top: 1.5em; margin-bottom: 0px; font-family: &quot;Open Sans&quot;, Arial, sans-serif; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); line-height: 1.3em; font-size: 28px; background: 0px 0px rgb(246, 249, 251); padding: 0px 0px 0.5em; border: 0px; outline: 0px; text-size-adjust: 100%; vertical-align: baseline;\">Lowering the Tongue</h2><p style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 0px; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background: 0px 0px rgb(246, 249, 251); padding: 0px 0px 1em; border: 0px; outline: 0px; text-size-adjust: 100%; vertical-align: baseline; font-family: &quot;Open Sans&quot;, Arial, sans-serif;\">Your tongue is great for things like talking to friends and eating ice cream, but for singing – not so much.<span id=\"more-2241\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; text-size-adjust: 100%; vertical-align: baseline; background: 0px 0px;\"></span></p><p style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 0px; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background: 0px 0px rgb(246, 249, 251); padding: 0px 0px 1em; border: 0px; outline: 0px; text-size-adjust: 100%; vertical-align: baseline; font-family: &quot;Open Sans&quot;, Arial, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; text-size-adjust: 100%; vertical-align: baseline; background: 0px 0px; font-weight: 700;\">Have you ever seen a tongue at the local butcher? Notice how big and tough it is?</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 0px; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background: 0px 0px rgb(246, 249, 251); padding: 0px 0px 1em; border: 0px; outline: 0px; text-size-adjust: 100%; vertical-align: baseline; font-family: &quot;Open Sans&quot;, Arial, sans-serif;\">Your tongue is a remarkably strong muscle that extends well beyond what you see in the mirror or occasionally stick out at people. It continues well down into your throat and tends to block your sound.</p><p style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 0px; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background: 0px 0px rgb(246, 249, 251); padding: 0px 0px 1em; border: 0px; outline: 0px; text-size-adjust: 100%; vertical-align: baseline; font-family: &quot;Open Sans&quot;, Arial, sans-serif;\"><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" data-filename=\"image.png\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; border-style: none; display: block; width: 800px; height: auto; margin-bottom: 20px; border-radius: 20px;\"></p><p style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 0px; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background: 0px 0px rgb(246, 249, 251); padding: 0px 0px 1em; border: 0px; outline: 0px; text-size-adjust: 100%; vertical-align: baseline; font-family: &quot;Open Sans&quot;, Arial, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; text-size-adjust: 100%; vertical-align: baseline; background: 0px 0px; font-weight: 700;\">You have to learn to get that big, clunky muscle out of the way of your voice.</span>&nbsp;The tongue needs to be trained to lay flat in the back of your mouth and come&nbsp;<em style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; text-size-adjust: 100%; vertical-align: baseline; background: 0px 0px;\">forward</em>&nbsp;in the throat. This takes some time and daily exercises with a mirror. Think of when you go to the doctor and they stick a tongue depressor in your mouth and tell you to say “Ah!”. You want to get your tongue to do just that on its own.</p><p style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 0px; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background: 0px 0px rgb(246, 249, 251); padding: 0px 0px 1em; border: 0px; outline: 0px; text-size-adjust: 100%; vertical-align: baseline; font-family: &quot;Open Sans&quot;, Arial, sans-serif;\">Place your thumb and index finger on your throat, as if you were feeling your glands when you’re sick. You should feel the base of your tongue. Open your mouth and gently yet strongly pull the tongue down in the back and forward in the throat. It feels like a very slight gag. With time and regular repetition, you will be able to condition the tongue to move down and forward with little effort or tension.</p><h2 style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-top: 1.5em; margin-bottom: 0px; font-family: &quot;Open Sans&quot;, Arial, sans-serif; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); line-height: 1.3em; font-size: 28px; background: 0px 0px rgb(246, 249, 251); padding: 0px 0px 0.5em; border: 0px; outline: 0px; text-size-adjust: 100%; vertical-align: baseline;\">Not the “Melocchi” Method</h2><p style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 0px; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background: 0px 0px rgb(246, 249, 251); padding: 0px 0px 1em; border: 0px; outline: 0px; text-size-adjust: 100%; vertical-align: baseline; font-family: &quot;Open Sans&quot;, Arial, sans-serif;\">There is more than one school of thought on the subject of tongue-lowering as the tongue is closely related in the body to the larynx, which is the muscle that holds your vocal cords. When you press the tongue down and forward, you are inadvertently also pushing your larynx down via the epiglottis, which may cause eventual vocal damage if not done correctly.</p><p style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 0px; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background: 0px 0px rgb(246, 249, 251); padding: 0px 0px 1em; border: 0px; outline: 0px; text-size-adjust: 100%; vertical-align: baseline; font-family: &quot;Open Sans&quot;, Arial, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; text-size-adjust: 100%; vertical-align: baseline; background: 0px 0px; font-weight: 700;\">『The idea of the lowering of the tongue should not be confused with what is known as “The Melocchi Method”.</span>&nbsp;Arturo di Giuseppe Melocchi&nbsp;(1879 -1960) was an Italian baritone and voice teacher and is best known for creating a singing method which depressed the tongue and larynx fully down.&nbsp;<span style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; text-size-adjust: 100%; vertical-align: baseline; background: 0px 0px; font-weight: 700;\">This method destroyed many singers.</span>&nbsp;The only singer who survived Melocchi’s method was Italian dramatic tenor Mario Del Monaco, who probably had steel vocal cords, anyway.』 - from Musical U(Vocal Technique: making space)</p><p style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 0px; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background: 0px 0px rgb(246, 249, 251); padding: 0px 0px 1em; border: 0px; outline: 0px; text-size-adjust: 100%; vertical-align: baseline; font-family: &quot;Open Sans&quot;, Arial, sans-serif;\">The great Italian tenor Franco Corelli was seeking out Melocchi Method for training, he modified the method. Instead of using force, in Corelli’s method, the larynx is gently and moderately pushed down, remaining buoyant and agile.</p><p style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 0px; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background: 0px 0px rgb(246, 249, 251); padding: 0px 0px 1em; border: 0px; outline: 0px; text-size-adjust: 100%; vertical-align: baseline; font-family: &quot;Open Sans&quot;, Arial, sans-serif;\">Another place the tongue gets in the way is with consonants such as “<em style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; text-size-adjust: 100%; vertical-align: baseline; background: 0px 0px;\">l</em>”. Voice the letter “<em style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; text-size-adjust: 100%; vertical-align: baseline; background: 0px 0px;\">l</em>” and note what happens to your tongue. It feels quite tense. When you must sing an “<em style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; text-size-adjust: 100%; vertical-align: baseline; background: 0px 0px;\">l</em>” consonant,&nbsp;<span style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; text-size-adjust: 100%; vertical-align: baseline; background: 0px 0px; font-weight: 700;\">gently touch the back of your front teeth with the tip of the tongue</span>&nbsp;and it will sound without causing tension. The same is true for the “explosive consonants” (“<em style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; text-size-adjust: 100%; vertical-align: baseline; background: 0px 0px;\">d</em>”, “<em style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; text-size-adjust: 100%; vertical-align: baseline; background: 0px 0px;\">t</em>”, etc).</p><p style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 0px; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background: 0px 0px rgb(246, 249, 251); padding: 0px 0px 1em; border: 0px; outline: 0px; text-size-adjust: 100%; vertical-align: baseline; font-family: &quot;Open Sans&quot;, Arial, sans-serif;\">Corelli was a master at making space for the voice which is evident at the example below. Notice how during the final high note of the Neapolitan song<em style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; text-size-adjust: 100%; vertical-align: baseline; background: 0px 0px;\">&nbsp;Core ‘ngrato</em>&nbsp;his tongue is completely pressed flat (and no doubt forward!) in his throat:</p><p style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 0px; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background: 0px 0px rgb(246, 249, 251); padding: 0px 0px 1em; border: 0px; outline: 0px; text-size-adjust: 100%; vertical-align: baseline; font-family: &quot;Open Sans&quot;, Arial, sans-serif;\"><iframe frameborder=\"0\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/4lfeyNFMWY4?start=195\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" class=\"note-video-clip\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; display: block; width: 353px; height: 240px; margin-bottom: 20px; border-radius: 20px; border-width: initial; border-style: none;\"></iframe></p><p style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 0px; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background: 0px 0px rgb(246, 249, 251); padding: 0px 0px 1em; border: 0px; outline: 0px; text-size-adjust: 100%; vertical-align: baseline; font-family: &quot;Open Sans&quot;, Arial, sans-serif;\">It might be difficult to see the exact location of Corelli\'s larynx while he\'s singing, but you might be able to see it completely flat and not moving at all if you focus on seeing his larynx. Of course, Corelli modified Melocchi\'s technique as this article said before. That\'s the point of this technique, and his breath support should be strongly involved as we can assume. One thing that we can exactly identify from his technique is this technique looks perfect to sing opera and it doesn\'t look to have any problems. However, the reason that many singers failed to attempt to learn is that there are many risks to ruining their instruments while learning the method because of tensions.</p><p style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 0px; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background: 0px 0px rgb(246, 249, 251); padding: 0px 0px 1em; border: 0px; outline: 0px; text-size-adjust: 100%; vertical-align: baseline; font-family: &quot;Open Sans&quot;, Arial, sans-serif;\">There are only some singers who are singing based on this technique on our planet. They are super famous opera star singers and they are most Spinto and Dramatico according to the Vocal fach. One of my past voice teachers said that the technique is usually optimized for the dramatic spinto voice because if the larynx goes down and keep their pose flat during singing, the \"Chiaro-Scuro\" should be dark and thick. That\'s why most dramatic voices usually sing this way. But light and agile voices such as leggiero and lyric and lyric coloratura should sing very light and bright except for some atmosphere of the whole story in the operas. But, as I have been researching this technique, keeping the position down of the larynx during singing requires lots of energy. However, it can possibly sound control remarkable up and down and ppppp through fffff like messa di voce.</p><p style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 0px; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background: 0px 0px rgb(246, 249, 251); padding: 0px 0px 1em; border: 0px; outline: 0px; text-size-adjust: 100%; vertical-align: baseline; font-family: &quot;Open Sans&quot;, Arial, sans-serif;\">That\'s why I think there should not be any controversy in the efficiency of this vocal technique. Just it is hard to achieve this technique to make a singers\' career success.</p><p style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 0px; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background: 0px 0px rgb(246, 249, 251); padding: 0px 0px 1em; border: 0px; outline: 0px; text-size-adjust: 100%; vertical-align: baseline; font-family: &quot;Open Sans&quot;, Arial, sans-serif;\"><br style=\"box-sizing: inherit;\"><br style=\"box-sizing: inherit;\">article source from musical-u.com/learn/vocal-technique-making-space</p>', '2023-06-15 19:32:53.000000', '2023-06-15 19:33:47.671737', '2024-07-29 19:27:43.090588', 'published', 1);
